---
const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why pay for this when LM Studio and AnythingLLM are free?",
    a: "Different problem. LM Studio is a model runner — it lets you chat with a local model. AnythingLLM is a RAG product — it lets you ask questions over your documents. Pumkin is an agent IDE — it lets you build named agents with specific tools and audit every call they make. If you've tried wiring agents together by hand using the Ollama API + MCP servers, you know how much glue this saves. The $99 is for the saved weekend of building it yourself.",
  },
  {
    q: "What do I need installed on my machine?",
    a: "Just Ollama (free, from ollama.com). Pumkin's installer bundles Node.js and everything else. No Rust, no Visual Studio, no Python. Run the .exe, you're done.",
  },
  {
    q: "Is Pumkin open source?",
    a: "Yes — Pumkin is free and open source under the MIT license. The full source is on GitHub: read it, modify it, fork it, even ship your own version. No license key, no account, no paid tier. It runs entirely on your machine.",
  },
  {
    q: "Mac and Linux support?",
    a: "Windows installer ships today. Mac and Linux are next — the Tauri shell is cross-platform; the bottleneck is getting the bundled-Node + code-signing story working on each platform. Founding license holders get all platforms when they ship, no upcharge.",
  },
  {
    q: "What if it doesn't work for me?",
    a: "30-day refund, no questions, no forms. Email and you get your money back. If you're past 30 days and a major version update breaks your workflow, email anyway — I'm one person and I'll work it out with you.",
  },
  {
    q: "What about updates?",
    a: "Lifetime updates for all v0.x releases. v1.0 (when it ships) will likely be a paid upgrade for new buyers, but founding license holders get it free.",
  },
  {
    q: "Why $99? Why a founding license cap?",
    a: "Because I want to ship something real and not a Series-A pitch deck. 50 founding licenses at $99 funds the code-signing certs, the macOS/Linux build work, and a year of development. After 50, price goes up — probably to $149 or $199 — and I get to keep building based on actual user feedback rather than guessing.",
  },
  {
    q: "Who built this?",
    a: "An indie founder under Software For Humans, LLC, based in Virginia, USA. Track record of building, shipping, and supporting small tools. Not a venture-backed startup. Not a side project of a bigger company. Just one person who wanted this thing to exist.",
  },
];
---

<section id="faq" class="section">
  <div class="container prose">
    <h2>Honest answers.</h2>
    <div class="faqs">
      {faqs.map((f) => (
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>{f.q}</summary>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </details>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .faqs { margin-top: 2rem; }
  .faq-item {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--brand-border);
    padding: 1.25rem 0;
  }
  .faq-item:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .faq-item summary {
    font-weight: 700;
    cursor: pointer;
    color: var(--brand-fg);
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }
  .faq-item summary::-webkit-details-marker { display: none; }
  .faq-item summary::before {
    content: "+";
    color: var(--brand-accent-quiet);
    font-weight: 800;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    line-height: 1;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
  }
  .faq-item[open] summary::before { content: "−"; }
  .faq-item p {
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    font-size: 0.9375rem;
    color: var(--brand-fg-muted);
  }
</style>
